result.execSummary:
The defendant Chue Vang was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Chue Vang in court with attorney Stephen Michael Govin.  Brad Alan Vorpahl appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Deputy court clerk: LMS.

The defendant has complied with the Deferred Prosecution Agreement.
On motion of the state, the court amended the charge to Criminal Trespass to Dwelling, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 943.14 a class A misdemeanor.  Court ordered entry of judgment of conviction to the amended charge.

Court sentenced defendant to serve 2 DAYS in the House of Correction CONSECUTIVE to any sentence with credit for 2 days served; TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

Restitution is set at $0.

Court orders defendant to pay all cost, fees and surcharges, including DNA surcharge by 5/8/2015 or a civil judgment to be entered with tax intercept.  Bail on deposit to be applied if applicable.
